The eyes are positioned dorsolaterally. They are placed at 20–26 % of the distance between the anterior tip of the snout and the trunk-tail junction. The nares are oriented anterolaterally and are closer to the snout than to the eyes. The internarial distance ( IND ) is 40–52 % of the interorbital distance (IOD). The spiracle is sinistral. The spiracular tube is directed posteriorly and dorsally (approx. 27 ° in lateral view,
Fig. 1
), and opens laterally. Its medial part is fused to the abdominal wall (but forms a shallow rim); the lateral circumference of the orifice is free. The opening of the spiraculum is positioned at 60–66 % of the head-trunk length. The anal siphon is dextral.
